Stored Procedure
A Stored Procedure is a pre-written set of SQL queries stored in the database that can be executed with a single command (Instead of writing the same SQL again and again you store it once and just call it like a function)

Why Stored Procedure
Avoid writing repeated queries, improve performance, Organize complex logic, Add security.

When 
Complex business logic, reuse queries many times, input parameters, control access.

DELIMITER //
CREATE PROCEDURE procedure_name()
BEGIN
               --SQL queries--
END //

DELIMITER
CALL procedure_name();

TO Drop
DROP PROCEDURE procedure_name;

In SQL Server
CREATE PROCEDURE @param1 datatype, @param2 datatype	
AS 
BEGIN
SELECT column1, column2
FROM table_name
WHERE columnN = @paramN;
END;

To run a Stored Procedure: EXEC procedure_name @param1 = ‘value1’, @param2 = ‘value2’;

IN Parameter: We send a value into the procedure, the procedure uses it and does not return it back.

OUT Parameter: Procedure calculates something and sends results back.

1.	Get Customer details By ID
DELIMITER // 
CREATE PROCEDURE GetCustomerByID(IN cust_id INT) 
BEGIN 
            SELECT customer_id, first_name, last_name, email 
            FROM customer
            WHERE customer_id = cust_id; 
END // 
DELIMITER ;

CALL GetCustomerByID(5);

Exp: Here we are creating a Stored Procedure called GetCustomerByID, this procedure is taking customer id as input. BEGIN starts the body of procedure where we fetch customer details then end the procedure. Call runs the procedure and get details for ID 5.

2.	Find total number of rents
DELIMITER //
CREATE PROCEDURE GetTotalRentals(OUT total_rentals INT)
BEGIN
    SELECT COUNT(*) INTO total_rentals
    FROM rental;
END //

DELIMITER ;

CALL GetTotalRentals(@total);
SELECT @total;

Exp: Here we are creating procedure name GetTotalRentals. In this query the OUT parameter will be returning the value. Here we are counting the total rows in ‘rent’ and stores the result in OUT in total_rentals. CALL functions runs the procedure and store result in @total and then SELECT @total shows the value stored in @total.

3.	Counting rentals for a specific customer

DELIMITER //

CREATE PROCEDURE GetRentalCountByCustomer(
    IN cust_id INT,
    OUT total_rentals INT
)
BEGIN
    SELECT COUNT(*) INTO total_rentals
    FROM rental
    WHERE customer_id = cust_id;
END //

DELIMITER ;

CALL GetRentalCountByCustomer(3, @count);
SELECT @count;

Exp: For this we are creating Stored Procedure GetRentalCountByCustomer, we are providing customer ID and need result for number of rentals. 

Dynamic SQL
It is a technique where SQL statements are built and executed at runtime instead of being fixed. It allows queries to change based on user input, program logic, conditions which make it flexible.

When: Table or column names not known in advance, filters depends on user input, queries need to change dynamically.

Ex: Search customers by first name
DELIMITER //

CREATE PROCEDURE SearchCustomerByName(IN name_input VARCHAR(50))
BEGIN
    SET @sql = CONCAT(
        'SELECT customer_id, first_name, last_name 
         FROM customer 
         WHERE first_name LIKE "%', name_input, '%"'
    );

    PREPARE stmt FROM @sql;
    EXECUTE stmt;
    DEALLOCATE PREPARE stmt;
END //

DELIMITER ;

CALL SearchCustomerByName('AN');

Exp: Here we are building query as a string, concat() joins parts together. Prepare converts string into executable statement.

Indexing
It is a technique used to speed up data retrieval operations by minimizing the number of accesses required to locate records.

Types of Indexing Methods
1.	Clustered Indexing
It stores the actual data rows in sorted order based on the index. It is always a primary key. There will be only one clustered index per table.
2.	Non-clustered Indexing
It stores index separately and points to actual data. Here the table data is not sorted only the index is.

Ex of Non-clustered index
                  Without Indexing

EXPLAIN SELECT *
FROM payment
WHERE amount = 2.99;

Here the type will be ‘All’ as it scans every row in payment table.

With Indexing

CREATE INDEX idx_payment_amount
ON payment(amount);

Here the type will be ‘ref’, it goes it index find all rows where amount = 2.99 and fetch only those rows. 

With primary key

EXPLAIN SELECT *
FROM payment
WHERE amount = 2.99
AND payment_id = 10;

Here the type will be ‘const’, it jumps directly to the exact row no more scanning.
